



Yes. That approach makes more sense than memorizing nouns.

The industry evolved by hitting constraints.
Each primitive exists because the previous layer broke.

Think of the whole thing as one long story:

1. First primitive: one machine, one program
At the beginning, you had:

one physical computer

one operating system

one program

one user or a few users

The core problem: how do multiple programs share one machine?

That created the first real primitives:

processes: separate running programs

memory management: keep programs from corrupting each other

filesystems: persist data after power loss

permissions/users: stop one person or program from touching everything

threads: let one program do multiple things at once

So the operating system emerged as the traffic cop of scarcity:

scarce CPU

scarce memory

scarce disk

scarce trust

That is why Linux knowledge matters.
Linux sits close to those original scarcity constraints.

2. Then came local networks
One machine did not suffice.

Companies wanted:

shared files

shared printers

shared databases

multiple machines cooperating

Now the problem changed from:
how do programs share one computer?
to:
how do computers talk to each other reliably?

That created networking primitives:

IP: how to address machines

TCP: how to send ordered, reliable streams

UDP: how to send fast, best-effort packets

DNS: how to map names to machine addresses

routing: how packets find a path

switching: how machines communicate inside local networks

ports: how many services share one machine

Why did these need to exist?

Because without them, every machine-to-machine interaction would require custom logic.
The network stack became the OS for many machines.

So networking primitives came from the need to coordinate distance and uncertainty.

3. Then applications became multi-user and stateful
Once networks existed, apps became:

email systems

internal company tools

websites

transactional systems

Now the problem became:
where does the shared truth live?

That created data/storage primitives:

databases: structured state

transactions: make groups of writes consistent

indexes: make reads fast

RAID: protect against drive failure

LVM: flexibly manage disk volumes

filesystems: better safety/performance tradeoffs

backups: survive human or machine error

Why?

Because disks fail.
Humans make mistakes.
Applications need durable shared truth.

So storage primitives came from the need to solve time:

keep data across reboots

keep it through failures

retrieve it fast later

4. Then the web arrived
Now software had to serve:

thousands

then millions

then global traffic

A single machine became a bottleneck.

The new problem:
how do we scale beyond one box?

That created:

load balancers: distribute requests

caches: reduce repeated expensive work

replication: duplicate data/services

sharding: split data across machines

queues: decouple producers and consumers

CDNs: move content closer to users

Why necessary?

Because one machine hits limits in:

CPU

memory

disk

network

geography

So the system stopped being “an app on a server” and became a distributed organism.

This marks the real birth of modern infrastructure.

5. Then distributed systems created new pain
As soon as systems spread across many machines, new failure modes appeared:

packets dropped

clocks drifted

one node lagged

networks partitioned

one machine had stale data

retries duplicated work

partial failures happened

This created a deeper set of primitives:

consensus/quorum

leader election

eventual consistency

heartbeats

retry policies

timeouts

circuit breakers

idempotency

backpressure

Why?

Because in one machine, failure looks binary.
In distributed systems, failure looks ambiguous.

A machine may be:

alive but slow

dead but not yet detected

reachable by some nodes but not others

partially written

duplicated

So these primitives emerged to manage uncertainty under coordination.

This becomes the heart of systems engineering.

6. Then hardware scale made manual work impossible
At small scale, a human can log into a server and configure it manually.

At real scale, that collapses.

New problem:
how do we make 100 or 10,000 machines consistent?

That created infra automation primitives:

PXE booting: boot and install machines over network

configuration management: Puppet, Ansible, Chef

infrastructure as code: Terraform

image-based provisioning

GitOps: desired state from version-controlled config

idempotence: rerun safely until desired state exists

Why necessary?

Because manual server work creates:

drift

inconsistency

undocumented snowflakes

fragile recovery

So automation primitives exist because scale demanded repeatability.

A good systems team no longer asks:
“Did we configure the server?”

It asks:
“Can we recreate the server from zero, correctly, every time?”

7. Then virtualization emerged
Companies realized many workloads underused physical hardware.

New problem:
how do we divide one machine into many isolated machines?

That created:

hypervisors

virtual machines

virtual networking

virtual disks

Why?

Because one app per server wasted money.
VMs increased utilization and flexibility.

But VMs still carried the weight of full guest operating systems.

So the next question became:
can we isolate applications without emulating whole machines?

That created containers:

namespaces

cgroups

container runtimes

images

orchestration

Containers exist because engineers wanted:

lighter packaging

faster deployment

environment consistency

denser packing than VMs

So:

VMs virtualize machines

containers isolate processes

That distinction matters because it tracks the historical constraint.

8. Then observability became necessary
When systems became distributed, debugging changed.

Before:

one machine

one app

one log file

Now:

many services

many machines

transient failures

shared dependencies

New problem:
how do we know what the system is doing?

That created observability primitives:

logs: event records

metrics: numerical trends over time

traces: request path across services

dashboards

alerting

SLOs/SLIs

profiling

Why?

Because modern systems fail in ways no one can see directly.

Observability exists to compress uncertainty into evidence.

Without it, ops becomes superstition.

9. Then cloud abstracted infrastructure
Cloud providers turned many hard primitives into rentable services.

Instead of:

buying servers

wiring racks

replacing disks

You could rent:

compute

object storage

managed databases

load balancers

queues

Why did cloud win?

Because early and mid-sized companies cared more about:

speed

flexibility

avoiding upfront capital expense
than perfect cost efficiency.

Cloud made infrastructure programmable.

But cloud did not remove the primitives.
It hid them.

That created a strange outcome:
many developers learned to deploy systems without understanding:

networking

storage

kernel behavior

hardware limits

That works until scale or performance matters.

Then the hidden primitives reappear.

10. Why companies like Databento still care about deep systems work
Databento deals with market data.

That means:

very high throughput

latency sensitivity

large-scale storage

deterministic ingestion and delivery

likely tight cost/performance demands

Cloud abstraction alone often costs too much or adds too much unpredictability.

So they move back down the stack:

bare metal

Ceph

25 GbE networking

physical data centers

custom tuning

That does not mean the industry moved backward.

It means the industry split:

For convenience:
use managed cloud

For performance and cost at scale:
relearn the underlying primitives

So the modern world contains both:

abstraction for speed

deep systems for efficiency

