12. The deepest pattern
Every primitive exists because one of these broke:

scarcity

distance

time

scale

failure

human inconsistency

lack of visibility

That is the whole industry story.

So when you see a term, do not ask:
“What is this definition?”

Ask:
“What constraint broke hard enough that this primitive had to be invented?”

That will make the field feel alive.

13. Where front end, back end, and systems fit in the tree
Front end
Lives closer to:

user interaction

rendering

browser/network edge

Back end
Lives closer to:

application logic

APIs

databases

service coordination

Systems
Lives closer to:

runtime substrate

machine behavior

networking

storage

automation

reliability

So systems engineering sits near the trunk of the tree.
Front end sits nearer the leaves.
Back end sits in the middle branches.

All matter.
But the trunk explains the constraints that the leaves often never see.

14. Why your instinct actually helps
You do not need to memorize this as isolated facts.

You need to keep asking:

What resource became scarce?

What new failure appeared?

What coordination problem emerged?

What primitive got invented to contain that problem?

That is how a systems engineer thinks from first principles.

15. The shortest example chain
A website gets popular.

Then:

one server becomes overloaded
→ load balancer

database becomes slow
→ index, cache, replication, sharding

deployments become inconsistent
→ config management, containers

outages become hard to debug
→ logs, metrics, traces

cloud bill becomes too high
→ bare metal, custom networking, storage tuning

That single chain recapitulates most of industry evolution.

The key insight:

Abstractions do not replace primitives. They stack on top of them until scale, cost, or failure drags you back down.

That explains almost everything in infra.

